    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Brighton 1 o'clock Satdy</p>
      <p>By giving a shilling fee to the guard of the 2 o'clock Train, he will put this into the post this evening in Town;-- &amp; I know it must be an object to you to get as many &amp; speedy Bulletins of me as possible.</p>
      <p>Indeed I am sure, my Dear, that you must find me very attentive in writing,-- do you not?</p>
      <p>You will have heard by parcel this evening.--</p>
      <p>I am anxious to write this afternoon, because I think there is a favorable change, both generally &amp; locally. It cannot but all proceed very slowly. But it is a great comfort to find it going so very decidedly in the right path now.--</p>
      <p>Today is too lovely to describe. I shall (later) go out again in the Chair;</p>
      <p>which is a great delight to me.--</p>
      <p>I have nothing particular, of course, to say. This is chiefly to assure you of my being improving rather than otherwise;-- &amp; still very comfortable &amp; happy. Dr King's kindess in looking in regularly twice a day (tho' he is overwhelmed with professional duties) is enlivening too.</p>
      <p>I often think</p>
      <p>of the bright sunny glowing black eyes of my fine strong Crow;-- who has taken so poor &amp; weak a little insignificant Bird to mate. She laid three rather fine eggs for him, but afterwards became very sickly &amp; continually moulted for many years.</p>
      <p>My dear, Your little Prisoner-Bird [horizontal line across page] (but she sings a little &amp; does not pine).--</p>
    </div></body>
